<div class="row recital_piece">
	<div class="holder">
		<h3 class="composition_title">Ludwig van Beethoven - Piano Sonata No. 8 in C Minor Op. 13 - "Pathetique"</h3>
		<h4 class="composition_name"> Movement I - Grave</h4>
		<p>Beethoven's Pathetique sonata is one of his most famous. Beethoven wrote it when he was just 27 years old and dedicated it to his friend Prince Karl von Lichnowsky. The piece was named "Grane sonate pathetique" by the publisher, because of its tragic sonorities.</p>
		<p>This piece just plain sounds cool. It is not terribly difficult, but the opportunity to learn a Beethoven sonata should never be passed up. what they may lack in difficulty they make up for by teaching you about tonality, stamina of theme, and wrapping a large work together.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="row recital_piece">
	<div class="holder">
		<h3 class="composition_title">Franz Liszt - An&eacuteenes de p&egravelerinage</h3>
		<h4 class="composition_name">Deuxi&egraveme ann&eacutee: Italie - Sonetto 104 del Petrarca</h4>
		<p>Franz Liszt composed his "Years of Pilgrimage" is widely regarded as a masterwork and complete summation of Liszt's compositional style. Its title refers to Goethe's novels "Whilhelm Meister's Apprenticeship" and "Wilhelm Meister's Journeyman Years". The Petrarch sonnets are pieces that are designed to be evocative of the corresponding sonnet. This particular sonnet is as follows:</p>
		<div class="sonnet">
			<p><i>"I find no peace, but for war am not inclined;</i></p>
			<p><i>I fear, yet hope; I burn, yet am turned to ice;</i></p>
			<p><i>I soar in the heavens, but lie upon the ground;</i></p>
			<p><i>I hold nothing, though I embrace the whole world.</i></p>
			<p></p>
			<p><i>Love has me in a prison which he neither opens nor shuts fast;</i></p>
			<p><i>He neigher claims me for his own nor loosens my halter:</i></p>
			<p><i>He neither slays nor unshackles me;</i></p>
			<p><i>He would not have me live, yet leaves me with my torment.</i></p>
			<p></p>
			<p><i>Eyeless I gaze, and tongueless I cry out;</i></p>
			<p><i>I long to perish, yet plead for succour;</i></p>
			<p><i>I hate myself, but love another.</i></p>
			<p><i>I feed on grief, yet weeping, laugh;</i></p>
			<p><i>Death and life alike repel me;</i></p>
			<p><i>And to this state I am come, my lady, because of you.</i></p>
		</div>
		<p>I chose to learn this piece after hearing a colleague in the piano studio play it. Its beautiful melody and impressive runs made it a great choice for my first Liszt work.</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="row recital_piece">
	<div class="holder">
		<h3 class="composition_title">Johannes Brahms - Sonata No. 2 for Piano and Violin in A Major</h3>
		<h4 class="composition_name">With Kyle Unruh - Violin</h4>
		<p>Johannes Brahms composed this sonata while vacationing in Switzerland. Its name suggests added importance of the piano part, rather than the usual "
		Sonata for Violin and Piano". The melodies include snippets from three songs that Brahms wrote earlier, and the first three notes from the first movement are almost identical to those from Richard Wagners "Walther's Prize Song" from his opera "Die Meistersinger von N&uumlrnberg. The piece is deceptively difficult, with complicated melodic/chordal integration and awkward chord structures.</p>
		<p>I struggled greatly with this piece. It was my first Brahms work, so I was entirely unfamiliar with his style of composition and melodic phrasing. I would have liked to continue working on the piece after my recital, as that performance was far from acceptable in my opinion.</p>
	</div>
</div>
